00:11:22.440 --> 00:11:28.280
I'm wondering if you might talk about your career arc through all of this, going from being

00:11:28.280 --> 00:11:33.000
a practitioner and kind of where you came from as you came into data science and then

00:11:33.719 --> 00:11:42.919
how that got you into teaching and community building. Oh, gosh. Sure. It's a windy story. So

00:11:42.919 --> 00:11:51.320
I was in my late 20s. I was working in the back office of a credit union. I have a strong

00:11:51.320 --> 00:11:55.880
background in retail banking. I was a teller for a long time, did all kinds of things in the

00:11:55.880 --> 00:12:02.280
backside. I worked for years as a debit card fraud specialist. I probably know more about

00:12:02.280 --> 00:12:10.520
debit card processing and debit card fraud than anybody should. But banks are full of data,

00:12:10.520 --> 00:12:15.159
full of information, and transactional information is extremely interesting.

00:12:15.880 --> 00:12:21.799
And so I got my sort of start with data as just a spreadsheet queen, right? Like I was in

00:12:21.799 --> 00:12:31.080
spreadsheets all day, every day. And when you only have customers who are using your product in a

00:12:31.080 --> 00:12:38.359
single locality, in my case, Austin, when something happens, you can triangulate what's happening,

00:12:38.359 --> 00:12:41.960
right? Like you can say, okay, all of these people have the same type of fraud.

00:12:42.599 --> 00:12:48.039
Where does this, what do they all have in common in the last six months? So you get to use your

00:12:48.039 --> 00:12:55.239
sort of like knowledge of what's going on, your subject matter expertise of, okay, I usually see

00:12:56.039 --> 00:13:01.719
someone's card be compromised within three months of it being used maliciously. So let's look back

00:13:01.719 --> 00:13:06.679
three months. Let's see what all of these cards have in common. Let's narrow it down and then

00:13:07.640 --> 00:13:11.239
boots on the ground type stuff. Let's start calling places and saying,

00:13:11.239 --> 00:13:17.640
have you seen anything suspicious? Let's talk to police, to detectives, to other people in

00:13:17.640 --> 00:13:23.559
other organizations, other credit unions, right? Who might be seeing the same thing.

00:13:23.559 --> 00:13:28.599
We can get information from them to help triangulate. That is how I started in data

00:13:28.599 --> 00:13:33.640
science, right? Just doing data science without really being called a data scientist. And

00:13:33.640 --> 00:13:39.400
I was working with neural networks back in like 2012, 2013, before a lot of people were,

00:13:39.400 --> 00:13:44.840
I was working with them as a sort of third party like service. And I was just blown away that I was

00:13:44.840 --> 00:13:50.359
working with machines that were learning. That broke my brain. I was like, I have to figure out

00:13:50.359 --> 00:13:56.679
how to do this. I'm so smart, but I did not have the economic opportunity to go to college of just

00:13:56.679 --> 00:14:01.719
like a lot of people. So I figured out how to do that. I quit my job. I went to college part-time.

00:14:01.799 --> 00:14:05.159
I went to college part-time. I started working at a tech company in Austin part-time,

00:14:06.200 --> 00:14:12.119
again, doing lots and lots of data stuff. And just like, it was just always a part of my job,

00:14:12.119 --> 00:14:17.799
but through every job, the through line was trying to get people together to solve problems

00:14:18.679 --> 00:14:22.039
and trying to get them together to talk to each other and help each other and do their jobs

00:14:22.039 --> 00:14:28.440
better. So I just continue to do that. I ended up getting a degree in management science,

00:14:28.440 --> 00:14:32.280
which is also called decision science. There's a big component of operations research in there.

00:14:32.280 --> 00:14:36.760
So mathematical optimization, programming, basically solving business problems with

00:14:36.760 --> 00:14:42.520
programming science and math. And then it went on to get my master's in data analytics,

00:14:42.520 --> 00:14:51.400
data science. So I learned R, SQL, Python, SAS, SPSS, all kind of within the same span of a few

00:14:51.400 --> 00:14:57.719
years, really got to get a good understanding of what I really, really liked. I gravitated

00:14:58.520 --> 00:15:05.320
much more strongly towards R, back towards R all the time. And I tutored a lot all through undergrad

00:15:05.320 --> 00:15:12.840
and grad school. And I also managed our grad cohorts Discord server. I put it together. I

00:15:12.840 --> 00:15:16.520
wanted to have a place where we could all get together and talk since it was during a pandemic

