tips you would give to folks trying to build community as well? Oh, nor. I love easy questions.

00:20:28.199 --> 00:20:34.359
I'm so glad that you asked this question is my favorite question. So the challenges of being a

00:20:34.359 --> 00:20:45.079
community builder are that people do not willingly volunteer to do things. And the tip that I would

00:20:45.079 --> 00:20:50.040
give anybody who's trying to build a community is to individually ask people to contribute,

00:20:50.040 --> 00:20:56.119
because there is a sort of like, misunderstanding global community. And I think that that's

00:20:56.839 --> 00:21:01.880
misunderstanding globally that happens where it's like, Okay, well, I want to get people together

00:21:01.880 --> 00:21:08.520
to share a diffused responsibility to do this thing that generally does not actually work.

00:21:08.520 --> 00:21:17.640
There has to be somebody or somebody's pair of people, maybe who are individually inviting,

00:21:17.640 --> 00:21:24.920
welcoming, asking, planning, scheduling, right. And the other piece of advice that I would

00:21:25.640 --> 00:21:35.800
give you is like, you need to find a balance between rigidity and structure and being free

00:21:35.800 --> 00:21:42.040
form, right? So the place where you need some structure is a schedule, same time, same place,

00:21:42.839 --> 00:21:48.280
beyond a consistent schedule, you will not meet everybody's needs, right? There will be a bunch

00:21:48.280 --> 00:21:52.599
of people who are like, I can't do that. I have a standing meeting at that time. That's okay.

00:21:53.319 --> 00:21:59.640
When they can make it, they will make it do things that are convenient to you as a community builder,

00:21:59.640 --> 00:22:04.199
because you are the one who is the only one who will always be showing up, right.

00:22:06.439 --> 00:22:14.040
And then where you don't want too much rigidity is in the sort of context of the meeting itself.

00:22:14.040 --> 00:22:19.319
If you if you prescribe it too much and say, this is exactly what we will do for every single minute

00:22:19.319 --> 00:22:24.439
of this meeting, you will have a bunch of people who don't know how to engage because they will

00:22:24.439 --> 00:22:29.000
constantly be worried that they're going to do the wrong thing, or have their hands smacked for it,

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:35.400
right? You will notice on the discord server that I do not generally bark at anyone if they post

00:22:35.400 --> 00:22:41.000
something on like a channel that doesn't make sense for that. Because I know that the most

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:45.719
beneficial thing is just having someone engage at all and having them welcomed and having their

00:22:45.719 --> 00:22:50.839
question answered and having a conversation. I don't care where you post stuff. I will probably

00:22:50.839 --> 00:22:55.239
let you know like, oh, did you know we have a hobby channel? And then that person could go,

00:22:55.239 --> 00:23:00.920
oh, wow, there's a hobby channel. Yeah, I'll go check it out. But yeah, those are my pieces of

00:23:00.920 --> 00:23:08.199
advice. Rachel, fill in all my gaps. What did I miss? No, I think that was great. And I want to

00:23:08.199 --> 00:23:13.160
make sure we get to a lot of questions. So I won't expand too much. But I think for me, the hardest

00:23:13.160 --> 00:23:21.400
part is being a people pleaser. And just I always want to make everybody happy. And when I read

00:23:21.400 --> 00:23:27.079
feedback, I'm like, oh, we should try this. We should try that. But you can't make every single

00:23:27.079 --> 00:23:32.280
person happy all the time. And I always have to remind myself about that. That's the hardest part

00:23:32.280 --> 00:23:38.119
for me. Absolutely. That definitely feeds into that. Don't try to ask everybody when they can

00:23:38.119 --> 00:23:43.800
make a meeting. Just set the meeting. Yeah. And that is maybe this can segue into like,

00:23:43.800 --> 00:23:49.079
I saw a question about someone who's hoping to start their own internal community. But I think

00:23:49.079 --> 00:23:57.319
that is the one thing I see from the most new organizers is people try and get everybody's

00:23:57.319 --> 00:24:03.560
feedback about like, what should the presentation topics be? What kind of workshops do you want to

00:24:03.560 --> 00:24:09.400
do? Which dates are best? Which location is best? And when you ask too many people for feedback,

00:24:09.400 --> 00:24:16.199
you just might not make it happen. You might not get started. And so I know Libby and I have joined

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:21.479
a few calls with teams who are starting to build their own community. And that is a piece of

00:24:21.479 --> 00:24:28.280
feedback we'll give them quite a bit is just get started. It doesn't have to be perfect from the

00:24:28.280 --> 00:24:35.560
start. But Libby, I think there's an anonymous question, but I see it is Mike from Datacore. And

00:24:35.560 --> 00:24:40.839
he said, Maggie actually referred him for this specific session. And Mike would love to start a

00:24:40.839 --> 00:24:46.839
data science hangout in Vietnam. What are the first steps? And does Posit support regional organizers?

00:24:48.040 --> 00:24:55.959
Oh, what a great question. The first steps are having a scheduled thing and also having a place

00:24:55.959 --> 00:25:01.000
where people can talk. So if you use Slack or Teams internally or your organization,

00:25:01.560 --> 00:25:06.760
setting up a place where everybody can talk and the conversations can continue is really great.

00:25:08.760 --> 00:25:15.400
And then instead of trying to sort of broadly say, hey, everybody come, everybody come, reach out to

00:25:15.400 --> 00:25:20.920
a bunch of individuals and say, hey, I really want to talk about data science together as a community,

00:25:20.920 --> 00:25:28.280
invite them one by one, bring them in. Because again, broadly asking people to volunteer for

00:25:28.280 --> 00:25:35.719
things is so much less effective. I would almost say ineffective completely compared to reaching

00:25:35.719 --> 00:25:43.239
out individually, talk to people one on one and get to know them. And then putting something on

00:25:43.239 --> 00:25:48.680
the calendar. Even if you start with two people, you and one other person and all you are doing

00:25:49.239 --> 00:25:53.079
is going, well, I don't know what to talk about. Here's what I'm working on today. Let me just

00:25:53.079 --> 00:25:58.199
show you what I'm doing and pair coding a little bit. You will grow over time into something

00:25:59.880 --> 00:26:05.400
that is good and that people will keep showing up for. Rachel, how about you?

00:26:05.400 --> 00:26:10.359
I wanted to see if Mike wanted to jump in and provide a little more context. Are you

00:26:10.359 --> 00:26:13.319
thinking like something virtually? Are you thinking in person?

00:26:14.199 --> 00:26:21.319
I think it can either be virtually or in person. It's just that we're not sure how to start it up.

00:26:21.319 --> 00:26:31.400
Or should it be once per two weeks? Or should we, as Libby mentioned, should we start within our

00:26:31.400 --> 00:26:36.920
company, even though it's a small company? I mean, a team that is relatively small, we also want to

00:26:36.920 --> 00:26:41.959
reach out to other universities, other labs that we want to involve people. But just where to start

00:26:42.119 --> 00:26:49.959
and then maybe can you guys also help if it's not a remote possibility? I just want to hear more.

00:26:52.680 --> 00:27:00.119
I would say think about what you could do consistently. Is that every other week? Is it

00:27:00.119 --> 00:27:06.680
once a month? If you make it easy for yourselves to get together, you can probably do it more

00:27:06.680 --> 00:27:11.640
frequently. But I think that consistency is so important. And that's what we've seen with the

00:27:11.640 --> 00:27:17.079
Hangout, because everybody knows that it's every Thursday at the same time, same place,

00:27:17.640 --> 00:27:23.640
people can come drop by when it fits their schedule. And I know not every single person

00:27:23.640 --> 00:27:27.880
here can make it every single Thursday. But you know, when you have an opening, you don't have

00:27:27.880 --> 00:27:35.239
a meeting, you know, the Hangouts here for you, and you can come drop by. So I would recommend

00:27:35.239 --> 00:27:43.880
that to make it consistent, whatever frequency you do decide on. But I also really love to remind

00:27:43.880 --> 00:27:50.040
people that you can start small. And that is perfectly okay. Like maybe it's five people

00:27:50.680 --> 00:27:55.880
getting together in the beginning. But be intentional about like following up with

00:27:55.880 --> 00:28:01.479
those people and asking what they thought about it, thanking them for being a part of it. And

00:28:01.479 --> 00:28:08.040
I'm sure they'll start to share it with other people as well. So again, yeah, start starting

00:28:08.040 --> 00:28:16.119
small is definitely okay. I think we probably had like 20 people in the beginning for the Hangouts.

00:28:16.119 --> 00:28:19.319
I was just gonna say how many people were at the Hangouts in the beginning, because I think it was

00:28:19.319 --> 00:28:29.880
like 12 to 15 initially in a lot of those like earlier things. But as far as how we might be

00:28:29.880 --> 00:28:33.959
able to help, I think that this is part of our help. Like we would love to give advice, but we're

00:28:33.959 --> 00:28:42.760
not we're not like in a position to officially host things worldwide, right, because of time zone

00:28:42.760 --> 00:28:48.839
restrictions. But I will say that one of my hopes is that as we grow over time, and we can't solve

00:28:48.839 --> 00:28:54.199
every single data science community problem in the world, but as we grow over time, I would love to

00:28:54.199 --> 00:28:59.959
help more and more people just get these little tidbits of information that can help them. So

00:29:02.119 --> 00:29:07.880
Mike, if you are on the Discord server, I hope you are. Find me, tag me in a channel somewhere

00:29:09.079 --> 00:29:15.000
so that I can see you and you can absolutely ask questions and we can help you. The biggest

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:21.880
pieces of advice, by the way, are still the same things. Set, calendar date, place to talk, and you

00:29:21.880 --> 00:29:26.439
already have the biggest component that you need, which is you, a person who wants this to happen.

00:29:27.800 --> 00:29:31.640
And it's great to have it inside your organization because then you can share about what you're doing

00:29:31.640 --> 00:29:35.479
and you don't have to keep things like secret or behind closed doors. You can share a little bit

00:29:35.479 --> 00:29:39.800
more openly with other people. So I do think that doing it inside your organization first would be

00:29:39.800 --> 00:29:44.839
really, really great, even though you're small. There's so much magic in just sharing with other

00:29:44.839 --> 00:29:54.520
people what you're working on. Just pair coding can just do so much. I wanted to hop into Slido

00:29:54.520 --> 00:30:00.280
and do a quick answer for one, because someone had asked, hey, around Christmas, we filled in a

00:30:00.280 --> 00:30:05.239
Data Science Hangout feedback thing, questionnaire. Are there any feedback highlights you can share

00:30:05.239 --> 00:30:13.400
with us? This is on Isabella and I's radar. We just worked on it right before we had our week

00:30:13.400 --> 00:30:19.479
off for work week, which was not really a week off, but we were off site. And so we will have

00:30:19.479 --> 00:30:26.920
something coming out soon. I am currently still working on it this week. I made the mistake of

00:30:27.479 --> 00:30:33.079
putting free text fields on almost every single question. And anyone who's worked with survey data

00:30:33.079 --> 00:30:41.000
knows that that is the thing that takes the longest. The biggest piece of feedback that I got

00:30:41.079 --> 00:30:49.400
from it was like, what would make things better? And far and away, the biggest one was more hands-on

00:30:49.400 --> 00:30:54.760
technical content, which made me really happy that we started the Data Science Lab. So if that is

00:30:54.760 --> 00:30:59.479
what you are looking for, and you would like more of it, come to the lab and let us know what you

00:30:59.479 --> 00:31:05.640
want to learn about. We are filling our schedule, Isabella and I, with people who can teach us

00:31:05.640 --> 00:31:10.760
hands-on things that we need to know. Next week, we're going to be joined by Charlie Gao.

00:31:10.760 --> 00:31:18.280
He's the author of Mirai. Mirai is an asynchronous programming package. He's going to teach us

00:31:18.280 --> 00:31:22.839
what is asynchronous programming? How does it differ from parallel programming? How easy is

00:31:22.839 --> 00:31:31.880
Mirai to use? How easy is it to scale your computing on demand? If you have multiple

00:31:31.880 --> 00:31:37.239
cores on your processor, how can you use them all at the same time to do your work more efficiently?

00:31:37.239 --> 00:31:41.880
These are things that are blind spots for me, right? I'm a more statistics flavored person

00:31:41.880 --> 00:31:46.280
than I am a computer science person. If that's you too, come to the Data Science Lab on Tuesday

00:31:46.280 --> 00:31:50.520
and learn with us, with Charlie. He's also just a wonderful human being, and you're going to have

00:31:50.520 --> 00:31:56.359
so much fun meeting him. Okay, Rachel, I'm going to leave the next one in your hands.

00:31:57.079 --> 00:32:04.280
Okay, I see Adam T asked a question. Adam, do you want to jump in here? Let me find you to unmute.

00:32:05.479 --> 00:32:12.199
There you go. I'm actually really glad to see you both as the leaders of the discussion,

00:32:12.199 --> 00:32:17.479
because especially when you mentioned people who have been to like 10 Hangouts, and I think

00:32:17.479 --> 00:32:22.599
this is number 10 for me, so it's kind of the perfect. I was like, all right, I'm now there.

00:32:22.964 --> 00:32:25.644
It's kind of the perfect I was like, all right, I'm now there.

00:32:26.124 --> 00:32:29.884
But this is a personal question, because I didn't come into data science

00:32:29.884 --> 00:32:31.244
through a data science degree.

00:32:31.244 --> 00:32:34.804
I went to university to do a few other subjects.

00:32:34.804 --> 00:32:36.884
None of them involved anything to do with computers

00:32:37.164 --> 00:32:41.804
until I found the value of learning data science to get through that subject.

00:32:41.804 --> 00:32:43.804
And now I work in it constantly.

00:32:43.804 --> 00:32:47.724
So when you meet people like all of us

00:32:47.923 --> 00:32:51.324
and I'm going now on a limb here that the two of you

00:32:51.444 --> 00:32:55.004
have probably seen more personalities inside of data science

00:32:55.004 --> 00:32:57.364
than any of the rest of us, because we're in our own little bubbles

00:32:57.364 --> 00:32:59.603
and you're seeing all of our bubbles.

00:32:59.603 --> 00:33:03.403
So the question is, what skills

00:33:03.684 --> 00:33:08.204
or backgrounds or habits or qualities do you see?

00:33:08.204 --> 00:33:10.284
And you start to think, actually, I want that.

00:33:10.284 --> 00:33:12.403
This person didn't have a data science degree.

00:33:12.403 --> 00:33:14.403
They had a degree in, I don't know, chemistry,

00:33:14.684 --> 00:33:17.684
but somehow they found their way into data science.

00:33:17.684 --> 00:33:19.964
And we want that because it's out of the box thinking,

00:33:19.964 --> 00:33:24.124
is that your thought process or is it more of a personality thing that you look for?

00:33:26.484 --> 00:33:30.404
Well, as someone who's not hiring data scientists,

00:33:30.404 --> 00:33:34.044
it's not things where I'm like looking for specifically,

00:33:34.044 --> 00:33:37.084
but I would say it's curiosity.

00:33:38.004 --> 00:33:41.044
I think it's when somebody sees like,

00:33:41.603 --> 00:33:46.483
oh, this there's this business problem or this came up in this company meeting.

00:33:46.483 --> 00:33:49.883
I wonder if there's a way that I could go and solve that

00:33:50.243 --> 00:33:55.483
or I could figure that out with data and then having like taking the initiative

00:33:55.644 --> 00:33:58.644
to go and like try something out and make it happen.

00:33:59.684 --> 00:34:05.004
So those are some of the best stories to me when you see like,

00:34:05.404 --> 00:34:09.124
oh, our president mentioned this, this challenge.

00:34:09.444 --> 00:34:13.243
I went and I like built this proof of concept

00:34:13.243 --> 00:34:16.243
and showed it to him to answer that question.

00:34:17.084 --> 00:34:21.404
That is almost exactly what I would say as well.

00:34:22.724 --> 00:34:27.724
Curiosity for me is the thing it's like meeting somebody

00:34:28.084 --> 00:34:33.443
who keeps asking questions in order to very obviously

00:34:33.443 --> 00:34:37.844
just get a better grip in their brain on the problem.

00:34:38.883 --> 00:34:40.924
Tells me like this person's invested.

00:34:40.924 --> 00:34:45.484
They are going to keep working on this until they they figure it out.

00:34:47.484 --> 00:34:51.284
The a good example is actually someone who just joined

00:34:51.564 --> 00:34:53.204
the Hangout for the first time this week.

