where we really internalized the mission of.

00:40:16.964 --> 00:40:21.363
Making a bunch of different people who are in the same space

00:40:21.964 --> 00:40:24.564
comfortable and at home where they are.

00:40:25.604 --> 00:40:31.483
And so if you would like to get a primer on welcoming and hospitality,

00:40:31.483 --> 00:40:34.323
go work in a bar, go work in a restaurant, right?

00:40:34.323 --> 00:40:37.684
And and figure out how to have a lot of different touch points

00:40:37.684 --> 00:40:41.004
with different people and also introduce them to each other.

00:40:41.004 --> 00:40:41.684
A lot of people

00:40:43.724 --> 00:40:46.923
come together, don't know each other, feel uncomfortable.

00:40:47.203 --> 00:40:51.004
The thing that you can do as the person who is willing to talk to all of them

00:40:51.004 --> 00:40:52.763
is introduce them to each other.

00:40:52.763 --> 00:40:54.483
And that's also a great way to grow.

00:40:54.483 --> 00:40:57.604
Any community is introducing people to each other because Rachel

00:40:57.604 --> 00:41:00.443
and I often talk about this, like think about if you were invited

00:41:00.443 --> 00:41:04.003
to a party where you didn't know anybody, you'd be so much less willing to go

00:41:04.643 --> 00:41:08.123
if you just weren't going to know anybody except for the host, right?

00:41:08.123 --> 00:41:11.003
The host can't spend all their time with you.

00:41:11.003 --> 00:41:13.763
But if you have a buddy who's also going to the party

00:41:13.763 --> 00:41:17.083
that you can hang out with and maybe that buddy knows a bunch of other people,

00:41:17.083 --> 00:41:19.323
you're going to feel a lot more like taking care of and

00:41:19.844 --> 00:41:21.804
and welcomed in that space.

00:41:21.804 --> 00:41:26.604
So introducing people to each other and also you as community members

00:41:26.604 --> 00:41:29.964
can help a lot by doing that same thing, inviting other people, saying,

00:41:29.964 --> 00:41:31.443
hey, this is really fun.

00:41:31.443 --> 00:41:32.443
Come hang out with me.

00:41:32.443 --> 00:41:35.083
I'll be in the chat with you and introduce you to people.

00:41:37.523 --> 00:41:38.763
There's so much.

00:41:38.763 --> 00:41:41.883
There's so much stuff I want us to cover in an hour.

00:41:41.883 --> 00:41:44.364
It's so hard to fit it in, but I'm glad you brought up

00:41:44.364 --> 00:41:47.643
the concept of like thinking of it as a party.

00:41:48.044 --> 00:41:51.763
Like if someone was showing up, it's someone coming to your virtual event.

00:41:51.763 --> 00:41:54.443
It's like someone's showing up at your door for a party.

00:41:55.883 --> 00:41:58.203
Yes, absolutely.

00:41:58.203 --> 00:42:01.203
Another thing that you can do, like Catherine Girton said in the thing,

00:42:01.203 --> 00:42:04.563
like good moderators make such a difference, that makes me feel great.

00:42:04.563 --> 00:42:07.364
Thank you, because that means that I think Rachel and I are doing a good job.

00:42:08.284 --> 00:42:12.523
But if you are in a digital space, good security goes a long way, right?

00:42:13.404 --> 00:42:18.804
So get to know your security tools with whatever event platform you're on,

00:42:18.804 --> 00:42:23.804
because you have a responsibility to take care of the people at your party

00:42:23.804 --> 00:42:25.643
and to protect them from bad actors.

00:42:25.643 --> 00:42:29.924
And it's the Internet, you know, like anything can happen on the Internet.

00:42:30.484 --> 00:42:33.284
But a lot less will happen if you understand

00:42:34.123 --> 00:42:36.844
Zoom security, Google Meet security, whatever it is.

00:42:37.484 --> 00:42:42.404
Yeah. And that's something we we had to change as the hangout grew.

00:42:42.404 --> 00:42:45.804
Like you may remember back in the day, we just let everybody join

00:42:45.804 --> 00:42:48.323
and be able to unmute whenever they want.

00:42:48.964 --> 00:42:52.724
And that's not just because like people were doing anything bad.

00:42:52.724 --> 00:42:55.964
It's like sometimes people accidentally unmute, too.

00:42:56.284 --> 00:43:00.484
So there's things that you kind of have to change as you grow as well.

00:43:01.964 --> 00:43:05.804
Abby, I see you had a question that you put into the chat.

00:43:05.804 --> 00:43:08.123
Do you want to go jump in here next?

00:43:08.123 --> 00:43:10.284
I'm going to highlight it and I'm also going to stick it in the chat

00:43:10.284 --> 00:43:11.683
for everybody to see.

00:43:11.683 --> 00:43:13.804
Hey, everybody. I hope you can hear me.

00:43:13.804 --> 00:43:16.563
Yes. Thanks. So multi-part question.

00:43:16.563 --> 00:43:21.404
Number one, what features, if any, do you wish you had on Zoom that do not exist

00:43:21.604 --> 00:43:24.804
that would make your your life hosting a lot easier?

00:43:25.883 --> 00:43:28.763
And then number two, do you get nervous before hosting

00:43:28.763 --> 00:43:31.044
and do you have any mantras that you tell yourself going in

00:43:31.883 --> 00:43:33.443
coming from a very nervous public speaker?

00:43:36.804 --> 00:43:39.563
Do you mind if I go first, Rachel?

00:43:39.563 --> 00:43:43.244
The thing that I wish Zoom did better is chat.

00:43:43.443 --> 00:43:46.083
If the chat did not bounce around like a bouncy ball

00:43:46.083 --> 00:43:49.924
every time somebody added something to a thread, that would be amazing.

00:43:51.003 --> 00:43:52.643
I really love chat in Discord.

00:43:52.643 --> 00:43:56.964
I wish that Discord could just be integrated into Zoom somehow.

00:43:56.964 --> 00:43:58.003
I think that that's way more fun.

00:44:01.003 --> 00:44:03.883
I think that Zoom.

00:44:05.203 --> 00:44:08.724
Is so you UI gooey based,

00:44:08.724 --> 00:44:11.804
it's like point and click, there's a million settings.

00:44:12.044 --> 00:44:15.484
And every time they have a major update, they change all of those.

00:44:15.643 --> 00:44:16.724
And that makes it much harder

00:44:16.724 --> 00:44:20.244
for anybody who is really relying on that to do their job, to do their job easily.

00:44:20.844 --> 00:44:23.643
That's what I wish was different was if I could code

00:44:24.123 --> 00:44:26.284
instead of point and click and zoom, I'd be a lot happier.

00:44:26.484 --> 00:44:29.683
But that's probably true for most things, including Jira,

00:44:30.683 --> 00:44:32.643
which we won't get into.

00:44:32.643 --> 00:44:34.003
And do I get nervous before?

00:44:34.003 --> 00:44:38.244
Absolutely. My hands start shaking 30 minutes before the hangout.

00:44:38.724 --> 00:44:39.643
On the dot.

00:44:39.643 --> 00:44:43.643
I know what time it is by whether or not I start like hyperventilating and shaking.

00:44:44.964 --> 00:44:46.724
It has gotten much better over time.

00:44:46.724 --> 00:44:49.083
And once I'm 10 minutes in, everything's better.

00:44:49.083 --> 00:44:54.164
But I think that the mantra that I tell myself

00:44:54.164 --> 00:44:57.123
without it really being a purpose thing is that.

00:44:57.924 --> 00:45:00.683
Everybody at the hangout wants me to succeed.

00:45:02.044 --> 00:45:05.284
And almost every single person, when you are in a room of people

00:45:05.284 --> 00:45:08.123
who are who you are talking to, do want you to succeed.

00:45:08.123 --> 00:45:10.683
If you are in a room of people who don't want you to succeed,

00:45:10.924 --> 00:45:12.683
you're in the wrong room, my friend.

00:45:12.683 --> 00:45:15.123
Get out of there.

00:45:15.123 --> 00:45:16.683
Run the other direction.

00:45:16.683 --> 00:45:17.604
You don't want to work there.

00:45:19.244 --> 00:45:22.003
If you're a person who is a people leader and you have

00:45:22.763 --> 00:45:28.203
a person on your team who is frequently needing to give presentations,

00:45:28.364 --> 00:45:33.203
you can do a lot by moderating, mediating, setting the tone in

00:45:33.964 --> 00:45:36.323
in places where they are.

00:45:36.323 --> 00:45:41.323
Giving talks to make sure that they are not blindsided by questions,

00:45:41.323 --> 00:45:44.443
helping them prepare, helping them put an appendix together, stuff like that.

00:45:44.883 --> 00:45:46.883
Rachel, what do you think?

00:45:47.683 --> 00:45:50.123
I think it's it's also something with chat,

00:45:50.123 --> 00:45:52.844
like I wish there was a way to pin things like, you know,

00:45:52.844 --> 00:45:55.604
when we share the Slido link and we have to keep resharing it,

00:45:55.604 --> 00:45:57.804
there's not a way to like pin it to the top.

00:45:58.883 --> 00:46:01.964
And yes, I definitely still get nervous for things,

00:46:01.964 --> 00:46:05.244
but not as nervous as I used to be for it.

00:46:05.244 --> 00:46:09.123
So I think it gets better over time, but it gets better

00:46:09.123 --> 00:46:11.203
because I know so many of you now.

00:46:11.203 --> 00:46:13.284
And so it's like I get to hang out with friends.

00:46:13.284 --> 00:46:16.244
It's not like I'm joining a group of people

00:46:16.244 --> 00:46:18.563
where I don't know who's on the other side.

00:46:19.484 --> 00:46:22.964
So I think that's definitely changed over time.

00:46:23.244 --> 00:46:26.123
But I like to remind myself people are coming

00:46:26.123 --> 00:46:29.724
because they want to be here and they want to be in this space.

00:46:30.003 --> 00:46:33.443
And that usually makes me feel a little bit less nervous.

00:46:33.563 --> 00:46:34.563
Yeah, yeah.

00:46:34.563 --> 00:46:38.404
And to the to my own point of like, everybody here is great.

00:46:38.643 --> 00:46:40.804
When you start small, like Rachel said,

00:46:40.804 --> 00:46:45.404
and you have people who are invested in this place being a good place,

00:46:45.724 --> 00:46:47.604
they are your bouncers.

00:46:48.604 --> 00:46:51.643
Mike made a joke about Marlene being a bouncer in our community.

00:46:52.643 --> 00:46:56.003
That is just the awareness that we have that if something

00:46:57.003 --> 00:46:58.003
smells bad,

00:46:59.003 --> 00:47:01.763
the people who are invested and who are a long time

00:47:01.763 --> 00:47:06.164
attendees, community members, are going to make sure that everybody is OK.

00:47:06.164 --> 00:47:09.123
They're going to, you know, as an organizer,

00:47:09.523 --> 00:47:13.523
Rachel and I are not the only people who care about this space being good.

00:47:13.844 --> 00:47:20.323
I know that somebody like Mike or or Marlene or Nellie or Hubert or

00:47:21.164 --> 00:47:24.724
Abby, you yourself, someone's going to get in there and be like, hey, now

00:47:25.643 --> 00:47:28.323
they're going to say something positive.

00:47:28.323 --> 00:47:30.323
I'm going to try and rapid fire answer

00:47:30.323 --> 00:47:34.724
a few questions like I see Arsenis asked a little bit about the behind the scenes

00:47:34.724 --> 00:47:37.323
stuff, like what goes into the hangout.

00:47:37.724 --> 00:47:42.883
And so just real quickly, like Libby and I have a spreadsheet

00:47:42.883 --> 00:47:47.083
with every single date of the hangout, like every Thursday.

00:47:47.484 --> 00:47:50.083
And we go in and

00:47:51.083 --> 00:47:53.484
when sometimes when we see posts on LinkedIn,

00:47:53.484 --> 00:47:55.883
we might connect with somebody or reach out to somebody.

00:47:56.083 --> 00:47:59.284
Sometimes we have people who work on the customer success team

00:47:59.284 --> 00:48:03.244
who reach out to us and say, like, I just heard this great story from so-and-so.

00:48:03.244 --> 00:48:05.244
They'd be a great hangout guest.

00:48:05.244 --> 00:48:08.244
And so we kind of just like plug people into dates.

00:48:08.244 --> 00:48:11.643
So we just reach out and say like, hey, would this work or would this work better?

00:48:12.044 --> 00:48:15.044
And we'd like to try and plan it out a few months in advance.

00:48:15.044 --> 00:48:18.044
Sometimes things have to get

00:48:18.044 --> 00:48:20.044
mixed up, pushed around.

00:48:20.044 --> 00:48:22.244
But then Libby has prep calls with people.

00:48:22.244 --> 00:48:25.044
So she gets to know them a little bit better.

00:48:25.044 --> 00:48:26.643
Gets to see what do they want to talk about?

00:48:26.643 --> 00:48:28.443
What do they not want to talk about?

00:48:28.604 --> 00:48:32.604
And then our web team puts that everything up on the website

00:48:32.604 --> 00:48:34.604
when we have all the info from them.

00:48:35.604 --> 00:48:38.604
Libby, you want to take a rapid fire question?

00:48:38.604 --> 00:48:39.604
Sure.

00:48:39.604 --> 00:48:42.604
And the only thing I will add to that is we try to have a balance

00:48:42.604 --> 00:48:45.604
of like different backgrounds, perspectives,

00:48:46.604 --> 00:48:48.604
areas of expertise, stuff like that.

00:48:49.604 --> 00:48:51.604
A rapid fire, let's see.

00:48:52.604 --> 00:48:55.604
What have been your favorite icebreakers or questions to ask

00:48:55.604 --> 00:48:57.604
and favorite answers you've got?

00:48:57.763 --> 00:48:58.763
From Nelly.

00:49:00.763 --> 00:49:03.763
I am terrible about having actual

00:49:05.763 --> 00:49:07.763
intentional icebreaker questions.

00:49:07.763 --> 00:49:09.763
I think Rachel's better at this one.

00:49:09.763 --> 00:49:12.763
I am much better about just sharing something funky

00:49:12.763 --> 00:49:14.763
that happened to me that morning.

00:49:14.763 --> 00:49:16.763
I spilled something on myself.

00:49:16.763 --> 00:49:18.763
Somebody left something weird at my door.

00:49:18.763 --> 00:49:20.763
It's usually me spilling something on myself.

00:49:20.763 --> 00:49:21.763
Let's be honest.

00:49:21.763 --> 00:49:25.763
Just something about me

00:49:25.924 --> 00:49:28.923
that's personal tends to be my own icebreaker.

00:49:29.923 --> 00:49:30.923
Rachel, what about you?

00:49:30.923 --> 00:49:32.923
Do you have a favorite icebreaker question?

00:49:33.923 --> 00:49:35.923
I don't know if I have a favorite one.

00:49:35.923 --> 00:49:38.923
I think it's usually when you say something that resonates

00:49:38.923 --> 00:49:41.923
with someone in the chat and it sometimes is completely unrelated.

00:49:41.923 --> 00:49:44.923
I get to see everybody going off about that,

00:49:44.923 --> 00:49:47.923
whether it's a book or a game that people are playing.

00:49:48.923 --> 00:49:52.923
Tim asked, what are common themes that we've noticed

00:49:53.083 --> 00:49:56.083
talking to successful Data Science Hangout leaders?

00:49:57.083 --> 00:50:00.083
I think my favorite Hangouts are always when it's somebody

00:50:00.083 --> 00:50:03.083
who has been an attendee for weeks and weeks.

00:50:04.083 --> 00:50:06.083
They're already a part of the Hangout crew

00:50:06.083 --> 00:50:08.083
and then they're the featured leaders.

00:50:08.083 --> 00:50:10.083
Those are my favorites.

00:50:13.083 --> 00:50:15.083
I know that's not necessarily a common theme,

00:50:15.083 --> 00:50:17.083
but that's something I've noticed.

00:50:18.083 --> 00:50:21.083
The thing that I have noticed as a theme is that

00:50:21.244 --> 00:50:28.244
successful leaders don't worry about not knowing everything.

00:50:29.244 --> 00:50:32.244
They worry about activating and enabling the people

00:50:32.244 --> 00:50:34.244
on their teams who know the things.

00:50:35.244 --> 00:50:37.244
And that they also are very driven

00:50:37.244 --> 00:50:40.244
by finding curiosity in others.

00:50:41.244 --> 00:50:44.244
And what Libby has pointed out before is like,

00:50:44.244 --> 00:50:46.244
we get on a prep call with people sometimes

00:50:46.244 --> 00:50:48.244
and they're like, I have nothing to share.

00:50:48.244 --> 00:50:50.244
Like, I don't have anything to share.

00:50:50.403 --> 00:50:52.403
Like, I don't know if this will be that interesting.

00:50:52.403 --> 00:50:56.403
And those end up being the most interesting Hangouts too.

00:50:56.403 --> 00:50:58.403
Every single person goes, me?

00:50:58.403 --> 00:51:00.403
You want me to be on the Hangout?

00:51:00.403 --> 00:51:02.403
No, no, no, I'm not the one.

00:51:02.403 --> 00:51:05.403
And then they'll have a super, super fun episode

00:51:05.403 --> 00:51:07.403
full of like all kinds of things.

00:51:08.403 --> 00:51:11.403
It's like, does everybody remember the one with Jim Weiss

00:51:11.403 --> 00:51:13.403
that we had where he was like,

00:51:13.403 --> 00:51:15.403
oh, I'm just a nerd who likes regression models.

00:51:15.403 --> 00:51:17.403
And we all like stood up collectively

00:51:17.403 --> 00:51:19.403
and we're like, which regression models?

00:51:19.563 --> 00:51:20.563
What do you do?

00:51:20.563 --> 00:51:22.563
Teach us all about your regression models.

00:51:22.563 --> 00:51:24.563
I was like, see, we're all just nerds.

00:51:25.563 --> 00:51:28.563
Libby, can I ask you the career advice question?

00:51:28.563 --> 00:51:30.563
Because we didn't do that one.

00:51:30.563 --> 00:51:32.563
What's your favorite piece of career advice?

00:51:33.563 --> 00:51:34.563
In three minutes?

00:51:35.563 --> 00:51:37.563
What's something that I wish that I had?

00:51:38.563 --> 00:51:40.563
I wish I could tell my younger self maybe.

00:51:44.563 --> 00:51:48.563
Get good at filtering the opinions of other people,

00:51:48.724 --> 00:51:50.724
especially if you're a people pleaser.

00:51:50.724 --> 00:51:53.724
Because if you have visions and ideas,

00:51:53.724 --> 00:51:56.724
the moment you ask other people about them,

00:51:56.724 --> 00:51:57.724
including what should I do?

00:51:57.724 --> 00:51:58.724
Where should I work?

00:51:58.724 --> 00:51:59.724
What job should I have?

00:51:59.724 --> 00:52:02.724
They will press their ideas upon you.

00:52:02.724 --> 00:52:05.724
So remember, realize that the advice

00:52:05.724 --> 00:52:07.724
that other people give you is about them.

00:52:08.724 --> 00:52:09.724
It's not about you.

00:52:09.724 --> 00:52:10.724
It's about what worked for them.

00:52:10.724 --> 00:52:11.724
Are you them?

00:52:11.724 --> 00:52:12.724
No.

00:52:12.724 --> 00:52:15.724
So just like take what they tell you,

00:52:15.724 --> 00:52:17.724
learn from it what you can,

00:52:17.884 --> 00:52:19.884
what you want, what fits for you.

00:52:20.884 --> 00:52:23.884
Jettison the rest of it directly into space.

00:52:23.884 --> 00:52:25.884
Rachel, what about you?

00:52:26.884 --> 00:52:29.884
I think it's to talk about the things

00:52:29.884 --> 00:52:31.884
that really matter to you

00:52:31.884 --> 00:52:33.884
and keep talking about it to people

00:52:33.884 --> 00:52:34.884
when you meet with them,

00:52:34.884 --> 00:52:35.884
when you're in meetings.

00:52:36.884 --> 00:52:37.884
Just keep bringing it up

00:52:37.884 --> 00:52:40.884
and you'll see that you get different

00:52:40.884 --> 00:52:42.884
opportunities offered to you.

00:52:43.884 --> 00:52:45.884
I think one lately that is not

00:52:46.043 --> 00:52:49.043
like advice that was given to me

00:52:49.043 --> 00:52:51.043
but that I've learned is...

00:52:53.043 --> 00:52:55.043
Okay, I might cry about this one.

00:52:56.043 --> 00:52:57.043
No, no.

00:52:57.043 --> 00:52:58.043
No, never mind.

00:52:58.043 --> 00:53:00.043
My grandma just passed away,

00:53:00.043 --> 00:53:04.043
but she was a nurse for 20 years

00:53:04.043 --> 00:53:07.043
and she decided she wanted

00:53:07.043 --> 00:53:10.043
to go back to school and became a CPA

00:53:10.043 --> 00:53:12.043
and eventually became a partner

00:53:12.043 --> 00:53:13.043
and an accountant.

00:53:13.203 --> 00:53:16.203
And I think it's never too late

00:53:16.203 --> 00:53:19.203
to go change what you want to do.

00:53:20.203 --> 00:53:21.203
Sorry.

00:53:22.203 --> 00:53:23.203
You made it through.

00:53:23.203 --> 00:53:24.203
You made it through.

00:53:24.203 --> 00:53:26.203
I will echo that.

00:53:26.203 --> 00:53:28.203
I told you all I was in my late 20s

00:53:28.203 --> 00:53:29.203
when I was like,

00:53:29.203 --> 00:53:31.203
I need a degree, right?

00:53:31.203 --> 00:53:33.203
Like I did not have the chance

00:53:33.203 --> 00:53:35.203
to do that when I was college age.

00:53:35.203 --> 00:53:36.203
It's never too late.

00:53:36.203 --> 00:53:38.203
I got my degrees when I was in my 30s.

00:53:38.203 --> 00:53:39.203
I did not learn how to code

00:53:39.203 --> 00:53:40.203
until I was in my 30s.

00:53:40.203 --> 00:53:42.203
I thought there's absolutely no way

00:53:42.364 --> 00:53:43.364
I'm going to be able to do this.

00:53:44.364 --> 00:53:45.364
But there is.

00:53:45.364 --> 00:53:46.364
You can.

00:53:46.364 --> 00:53:47.364
There are nice people

00:53:47.364 --> 00:53:49.364
who will help you do it.

00:53:49.364 --> 00:53:52.364
And there are people who believe in you

00:53:52.364 --> 00:53:53.364
and you're so much stronger

00:53:53.364 --> 00:53:54.364
than you think you are.

00:53:54.364 --> 00:53:56.364
You also contain multitudes.

00:53:56.364 --> 00:53:57.364
And if anybody is telling you

00:53:57.364 --> 00:53:58.364
to like pick a lane

00:53:58.364 --> 00:54:00.364
or find a thing that you like

00:54:00.364 --> 00:54:01.364
and do it,

00:54:01.364 --> 00:54:02.364
just know that you're

00:54:02.364 --> 00:54:04.364
a very complex human being.

00:54:04.364 --> 00:54:06.364
And some people do love one lane

00:54:06.364 --> 00:54:07.364
and they will love it

00:54:07.364 --> 00:54:08.364
until the day that they die.

00:54:08.364 --> 00:54:10.364
But if you like 18 lanes,

00:54:10.524 --> 00:54:12.524
drive in 18 lanes, my friend.

00:54:13.524 --> 00:54:14.524
I fully support that.

00:54:14.524 --> 00:54:15.524
Be a whole human being.

00:54:15.524 --> 00:54:16.524
All right, everybody.

